      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "While historical examples of sovereign defaults show that unsustainable debt can destroy an economy and leave social programs defunded, current global data suggests debt itself is not automatically the primary driver of collapse. The critical distinction often lies in whether debt is being serviced aggressively enough to cause a crisis versus staggering future obligations that simply crowd out domestic investment opportunities. Prioritizing debt reduction blindly could starve investments in infrastructure, education, and healthcare, thereby potentially weakening the very tax base needed to reduce that debt in the first place. Consequently, many economists argue that ignoring these critical funding needs doesn't prevent collapse but merely accelerates economic stagnation.",
